<paragraph id="296BD809A51B897D3FCD4154D02A432A" pageId="2" pageNumber="107">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5ABC406CFE51F79A3F9CBD12FE6BF83B" pageId="2" pageNumber="107">
All diagnostic features of 
<taxonomicName id="10AE1CE3957CAD45575739AB488390E5" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Microperus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Microperus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="107" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Microperus</taxonomicName>
present: small size, elytral punctures aligned in striae, and prolonged body shape (
<bibRefCitation id="398FAE044847BCC547EB7CB1191E9C0A" pageId="2" pageNumber="107">Hulcr and Cognato in press</bibRefCitation>
). Similar to 
<taxonomicName id="D4DC6C6F0809BD2371202F449D970FFA" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Microperus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Microperus pometianus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="107" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pometianus">Microperus pometianus</taxonomicName>
, but slightly longer, with distinctly elevated and long declivital costa.
</paragraph>
